1. Project Initialization & Setup Commands
To create and initialize your new project, run the following commands sequentially in your system terminal:

# Verify your local Node.js environment installation versions
node -v
npm -v

# Scaffold the boilerplate React application repository
npx create-react-app InstaCloneStarter

# Navigate directly into the newly created root directory context
cd InstaCloneStarter

# Initialize the development server engine 
npm start

2 & 3. Integrated Source Modifications (App.js & TrendingSong.js)
To keep everything structured, clean, and fast to implement, you can set up your components as shown below.

Create your Component File: src/TrendingSong.js
Create a new file named TrendingSong.js in your /src folder and paste the following functional component:

// src/TrendingSong.js
import React from 'react';

const TrendingSong = () => {
  return (
    <h2 style={{ color: '#1DB954', fontFamily: 'sans-serif' }}>
      Trending on Spotify: Calm Down
    </h2>
  );
};

export default TrendingSong;

Update your Main File: src/App.js
Open your existing App.js file, replace its entire contents with the following code to import TrendingSong and update your main workspace landing text:

// src/App.js
import React from 'react';
import TrendingSong from './TrendingSong';

function App() {
  return (
    <div style={{ textAlign: 'center', marginTop: '50px', fontFamily: 'sans-serif' }}>
      {/* Task 2: Main Heading */}
      <h1 style={{ color: '#E23744' }}>Welcome to My React Zomato App</h1>
      
      {/* Task 3: Imported Spotify Component */}
      <TrendingSong />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

4. Architectural Explanation: React Virtual DOM
Traditional DOM manipulation forces the browser to re-paint the layout of the entire web page even for minor text changes, which is computationally expensive and slow.

React solves this by creating a lightweight virtual copy of the real DOM in memory. When state updates occur, React changes this virtual tree first, compares it against
a snapshot of the previous layout (a process called Diffing), and then applies only the isolated changes to the actual browser DOM (called Reconciliation), preventing 
unnecessary and sluggish page re-renders.
